10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday. I realize I say that a lot, but =
I=E2=80=99m saying it again.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">FTX</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The obvious question =E2=80=94=C2=A0here and a=
lways =E2=80=94=C2=A0is: Is it a=C2=A0<em>liquidity=C2=A0</em>problem, or a=
=C2=A0<em>solvency=C2=A0</em>problem? Classically, if you are a bank, and y=
ou have $100 of perfectly good mortgages outstanding, $20 of cash in your v=
aults and $100 of deposits, and all the depositors show up one day asking f=
or their money back, you don=E2=80=99t have it. You have $20 of cash and th=
ey want $100. But you are=C2=A0<em>good for it:=C2=A0</em>You=E2=80=99ve go=
t $100 of good mortgages, and when they get paid back you=E2=80=99ll have p=
lenty of money for your depositors. You are just not good for it=C2=A0<em>r=
ight this minute</em>. You are=C2=A0<em>solvent=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0yo=
u=C2=A0have $120 of assets (loans plus cash) and $100 of liabilities (depos=
its) =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=C2=A0<em>illiquid</em>. This is <em>It=E2=80=99s a =
Wonderful Life</em>.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, if you have $100 of loans a=
nd $20 of cash, but $40 of the loans were to your chief executive officer=
=E2=80=99s brother-in-law to build a house in a swamp, and the house sank i=
nto the swamp and he=E2=80=99s never going to pay you back, then you have t=
o write down your loans to $60, and you only have $80 of assets. And when y=
our depositors hear about that, they will say =E2=80=9Chmm that sounds bad,=
=E2=80=9D and they all=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0</em>show up asking for their mon=
ey back. And you will only have $20, but that is not the main problem; the =
main problem is that even when (the rest of) your loans are paid back you w=
ill only have $80, and you owe them $100. Your assets are worth less than y=
our liabilities. No matter how long you wait, there=E2=80=99s not enough mo=
ney to pay back all the depositors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a nice clean distinction in theory but=
 very hard to see in practice. For one thing, if a financial firm is facing=
 a liquidity crisis, it=E2=80=99s usually=C2=A0<em>because=C2=A0</em>people=
 are worried about solvency: People don=E2=80=99t normally all rush to with=
draw their money from the bank unless they=E2=80=99re worried that the bank=
 is full of bad loans. For another thing, if people=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>a=
ll rush to withdraw their money from a financial firm, that can=C2=A0<em>ca=
use=C2=A0</em>solvency problems: To raise liquidity, the firm will sell ass=
ets, which will drive down the prices of those assets, which will make its =
remaining assets less valuable, which can leave it with assets worth less t=
han its liabilities.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still the distinction matters. Roughly it come=
s down to: If someone gave you enough time to sell all your assets =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0whatever that means exactly =E2=80=94 would you be able to sell th=
em for enough money to cover your debts?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the answer is yes, then you have a liquidit=
y crisis, and someone can probably fix it. You call up someone with a lot o=
f money =E2=80=94 J.P. Morgan, Jamie Dimon, Warren Buffett, the Federal Res=
erve, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and say =E2=80=9Chey we need some money to pay ou=
r current debts, which we were hoping you would lend to us, but we have ple=
nty of good assets, which we will sell at a leisurely pace over the next fe=
w months to raise enough money to pay you back.=E2=80=9D And then your pote=
ntial rescuer looks at your financial statements and evaluates your assets =
to see if it agrees that you are solvent, and if it does it gives you the m=
oney to solve your liquidity problem, and then you pay it back in good time=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And it charges you for this service. If you ar=
e a bank and your rescuer is the Fed, it might follow the <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmV=
kZXJhbHJlc2VydmUuZ292L25ld3NldmVudHMvc3BlZWNoL21hZGlnYW4yMDA5MDgyMWEuaHRt/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB051c8352" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> classic maxim</a> to =E2=80=9Cle=
nd freely, against good collateral, at a penalty rate=E2=80=9D: It gives yo=
u the money (=E2=80=9Clend freely=E2=80=9D), after checking to make sure th=
at you=E2=80=99re good for it (=E2=80=9Cagainst good collateral=E2=80=9D), =
but it charges you a high enough interest rate to make the rescue painful (=
=E2=80=9Cat a penalty rate=E2=80=9D). (In practice modern central banks oft=
en de-emphasize the penalty rate.) If your rescuer is Warren Buffett, he wi=
ll charge=C2=A0you an even higher interest rate and take <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly9xei5jb20v=
NjcwNTIvaGVyZXMtaG93LXdhcnJlbi1idWZmZXR0LW1hZGUtMy0xLWJpbGxpb24tb24taGlzLWN=
yaXNpcy1lcmEtYmV0LW9uLWdvbGRtYW4tc2FjaHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB92b87f6a"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> a chunk of equity upside too</a>; the deal will be expensive for =
you and attractive for him. But the simplest approach is for your rescuer t=
o charge you=C2=A0<em>everything you have:=C2=A0</em>You give the rescuer y=
our whole company, and you get back roughly zero dollars. (=E2=80=9CA Snick=
ers bar,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjItMTEtMDgvYmluYW5jZS1zLXpoYW8tc2JmLWVkLWZ0eC1zLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQ_Y21waW=
Q9QkJEMTExMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZ=
XR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBcbba2347" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  I said</a> the other day.) That is, the res=
cuer pays zero dollars for your <em>equity</em>. You have $120 of assets an=
d $100 of liabilities; the rescuer pays off the $100 of customer liabilitie=
s and gets the $20 of upside for free; you get nothing. If you are in fact =
solvent, if your assets are worth more than your liabilities, then the resc=
uer makes a lot of money from this deal. And you don=E2=80=99t have much ch=
oice: In this situation, often, zero is the best price you=E2=80=99re going=
 to get.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the answer is no =E2=80=94=C2=A0if the asse=
ts are all swamp loans to your brother-in-law =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you are i=
nsolvent, and no one is going to lend you more money, or acquire you for ze=
ro dollars. You are not worth zero dollars! You are worth less than zero do=
llars! You have lots of debts and not enough good assets! An acquirer who b=
ought your assets and liabilities=C2=A0for zero dollars would lose a lot of=
 money! At this point, the normal outcome is that you file for bankruptcy a=
nd your creditors get your assets, which are worth less than the amount the=
y were owed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But all these things are uncertain and decisio=
ns need to be made fast, so mistakes are made. Sometimes a rescuer will buy=
 a firm in a liquidity crisis for $0 after hasty due diligence, and will th=
en find out that it is in worse shape than it thought, so the rescuer will =
lose a bunch of money. Other times potential rescuers will look at a firm i=
n a liquidity crisis and conclude either =E2=80=9Cthat firm is insolvent=E2=
=80=9D or else =E2=80=9Cthat firm=C2=A0<em>might=C2=A0</em>be insolvent and=
 I don=E2=80=99t want the risk of finding out,=E2=80=9D and there will be n=
o rescue. But maybe it <em>would </em>have been solvent with a rescue. It i=
s hard to tell, though. <em>Without=C2=A0</em>a rescue there will be a fire=
 sale of assets followed by bankruptcy, which is often enough to <em>make=
=C2=A0</em>the firm insolvent even if it wasn=E2=80=99t already.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Tuesday it turned out that FTX.com, the big=
 cryptocurrency exchange founded by Sam =E2=80=9CSBF=E2=80=9D Bankman-Fried=
, was out of money. We talked about this on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDgvYmluYW5jZS1zLXpoYW8tc2JmLWVkLWZ0eC1z=
LWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWF=
pbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb2=
5leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCcbba2347" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Tuesday</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21h=
bi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1kZWF0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbXB=
pZD1CQkQxMTEwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2=
xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMTAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB3e317929" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  Wednesday</a>. Details remain somewhat sket=
chy but it appears that FTX has=C2=A0a lot of loans outstanding to Alameda =
Research, a crypto trading firm also founded by Bankman-Fried. It is certai=
nly possible that those loans are in the category of brother-in-law swamp l=
oans; in any case, customers got nervous and asked to withdraw money, and t=
he money was not quite there.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the same time that FTX disclosed its liquid=
ity problems it also announced that it had signed a nonbinding letter of in=
tent with Binance Holdings Ltd., the even bigger crypto exchange founded by=
 Changpeng =E2=80=9CCZ=E2=80=9D Zhao, to rescue FTX. The terms were not dis=
closed, but I assume they were along the lines of =E2=80=9Ccustomers get pa=
id out quickly at 100 cents on the dollar, and FTX=E2=80=99s equity investo=
rs get zero.=E2=80=9D (FTX=E2=80=99s equity was recently <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25i=
Yy5jb20vMjAyMi8xMS8xMC9zZXF1b2lhLWNhcGl0YWwtbWFya3MtZG93bi1pdHMtZnR4LWludmV=
zdG1lbnQtdG8tMC5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB11699bf4" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> valued at=
 $32 billion</a>.) But that deal was nonbinding and subject to due diligenc=
e, and it=C2=A0fell apart yesterday, with=C2=A0Binance announcing=C2=A0that=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmluYW5j=
ZS1zZWVuLWxpa2VseS10by1iYWxrLWF0LWZ0eC1kZWFsLWFmdGVyLXNwb3R0aW5nLWRlZXAtaG9=
sZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTEwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2=
U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMTAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB4f2a2f62" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  it will not proceed</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Compared to traditional finance, a liquidity p=
roblem in crypto is a bit worse =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a bit more likely to lead=
 to a solvency problem =E2=80=94=C2=A0for a couple of reasons:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In traditional finance, if you are il=
liquid and need a bailout, there are lots of people you can call who have a=
 lot of money and who are in more or less this business. The Fed, for one t=
hing, is very explicitly in the business of providing liquidity to solvent =
banks. But also there are hedge funds and big banks who, if they get a call=
 from a smaller competitor saying =E2=80=9Cwe are out of money, help,=E2=80=
=9D will send people to work all night doing due diligence, and who have pl=
enty of money to make deals. In crypto, there is no Fed, the whole industry=
 is new, the biggest players are=C2=A0<em>relatively=C2=A0</em>small, and n=
o traditional bank will touch it. I don=E2=80=99t know if FTX called up JPM=
organ Chase &amp; Co.=C2=A0to ask for a bailout, but I am quite certain tha=
t JPMorgan would have said no. FTX called Binance, which might be the=C2=A0=
<em>one=C2=A0</em>firm that could rescue it. Before this week, most people =
would have said that the=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>source of rescue capital fo=
r illiquid crypto firms was FTX. Oops.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">In traditional finance, your assets have cash flows. If you own some m=
ortgage bonds, and the prices of those bonds drop, and you think they will =
eventually pay off in full, you can just hold them until they do. Of course=
 you can=E2=80=99t if you are illiquid =E2=80=94=C2=A0so you might need a r=
escue =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if your rescuer has plenty of money then it can ju=
st wait until the bonds pay off. Today=E2=80=99s market price of your asset=
s is, arguably, not the only indicator of solvency. If the underlying asset=
s are good, then you will turn out to be solvent. In crypto, it is hard to =
know what =E2=80=9Cthe underlying assets are good=E2=80=9D could even mean.=
=C2=A0In crypto, if people lose confidence in some crypto asset, it can jus=
t go to zero and stay there. A big part of FTX=E2=80=99s trouble seems to b=
e reliance on the value of its own token, called FTT, whose price fell from=
 $22ish on Monday to $3ish today. =E2=80=9CWe will just hold on to FTX and =
it will recover=E2=80=9D would be a=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>risky thing for=
 a potential rescuer to think. <em>Why </em>would it recover?<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is a weird mix of opacity a=
nd transparency in crypto that might be unhelpful: Everyone can see trades =
and balances on the blockchain, so it is easy to start rumors and snipe at =
risky positions, but nobody publishes audited balance sheets, so it is hard=
 to inspire market confidence. =E2=80=9COur assets are fine and we have ple=
nty of capital=E2=80=9D is more compelling when a bank says it, with its pu=
blic audited financials, than when a crypto exchange does.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Look, there is a long history of scams and Ponzis =
in crypto, so if you have a liquidity problem everyone is going to assume t=
hat you are running a scam or a Ponzi.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This morning Bankman-Fried <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyL=
mNvbS9TQkZfRlRYL3N0YXR1cy8xNTkwNzA5MTY2NTE1MzEwNTkz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB4ca181aa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> tweeted an update thread</a>, <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS=
9TQkZfRlRYL3N0YXR1cy8xNTkwNzA5MTgxMDc3OTM0MDgx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB344=
22d6b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> saying that</a> FTX is =E2=80=9Cspending the week doing eve=
rything we can to raise liquidity=E2=80=9D to pay out customers. He also <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0=
cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9TQkZfRlRYL3N0YXR1cy8xNTkwNzA5MTcxMzM4Nzc2NTc3/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBee87ad34" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> described FTX=E2=80=99s situation as =
a liquidity crisis</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX International currently has a total market=
 value of assets/collateral higher than client deposits (moves with prices!=
).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that's different from liquidity for delive=
ry--as you can tell from the state of withdrawals. The liquidity varies wid=
ely, from very to very little.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Binance seems to see things differently. Its o=
fficial account <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29=
660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9iaW5hbmNlL3N0YXR1cy8xNTkwNDQ5MTYxM=
DY5MjY4OTky/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3b278b7e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> tweeted yesterday</=
a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a result of corporate due diligence, as wel=
l as the latest news reports regarding mishandled customer funds and allege=
d US agency investigations, we have decided that we will not pursue the pot=
ential acquisition of FTX.com.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the beginning, our hope was to be able to s=
upport FTX=E2=80=99s customers to provide liquidity, but the issues are bey=
ond our control or ability to help.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmluYW5jZS1zZWVuLWxpa2VseS10by1iYWxrLWF0LWZ0eC1kZWF=
sLWFmdGVyLXNwb3R0aW5nLWRlZXAtaG9sZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTEwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG=
1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMTAmdXRtX=
2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC4f2a2f62" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Blo=
omberg News reported </a>that=C2=A0Binance=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cexecutives fo=
und themselves staring into a financial black hole -- a gap between liabili=
ties and assets at FTX that=E2=80=99s probably in the billions, and possibl=
y more than $6 billion, according to a person familiar with the matter.=E2=
=80=9D So, insolvent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What should you make of this? Well, one thing =
to consider is that if FTX is solvent, and Binance has the opportunity to b=
uy it for $0, then that=E2=80=99s in=C2=A0<em>Binance=E2=80=99s=C2=A0</em>b=
est interests. FTX seems to owe customers <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2x=
lcy9mdHgtdGFwcGVkLWludG8tY3VzdG9tZXItYWNjb3VudHMtdG8tZnVuZC1yaXNreS1iZXRzLX=
NldHRpbmctdXAtaXRzLWRvd25mYWxsLTExNjY4MDkzNzMyP21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3BvczI/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB738bb22f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> about $16 billion</a>; if it has $17=
 billion of assets at market value, then Binance would be paying $16 billio=
n to get $17 billion of crypto assets=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>a more-or-less=
 functioning business that was recently valued at $32 billion. Seems like a=
 good deal. Whereas if Binance walks away, it mostly gets contagion, as cry=
pto prices fall and customers lose confidence in the whole industry. Binanc=
e had some incentives to conclude that FTX is solvent, but it couldn=E2=80=
=99t get there.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9TQkZfRl=
RYL3N0YXR1cy8xNTkwNzA5MTk3NTAyODEyMTYw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8ed8cba6" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> also tweeted this</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some point I might have more to=
 say about a particular sparring partner, so to speak. But you know, glass =
houses. So for now, all I'll say is: well played; you won.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I assume that is addressed to Zhao and Binance=
. What seems to have precipitated FTX=E2=80=99s crisis is that <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2=
l0dGVyLmNvbS9jel9iaW5hbmNlL3N0YXR1cy8xNTg5MjgzNDIxNzA0MjkwMzA2/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBb8eaa13e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> Zhao tweeted</a> that Binance would be sell=
ing its holdings of FTT tokens =E2=80=9Cdue to recent revelations that have=
 came to light.=E2=80=9D This undermined confidence in FTX, Alameda and the=
 FTT token, with the result that (1) customers took their money out of FTX,=
 sparking a liquidity crisis, and (2) FTX=E2=80=99s holdings of FTT lost va=
lue, sparking a solvency crisis. In an <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/29660451.274515/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9saXZlY292ZX=
JhZ2Uvc3RvY2stbWFya2V0LW5ld3MtdG9kYXktMTEtMTAtMjAyMi1jcGktcmVwb3J0LW9jdG9iZ=
XItaW5mbGF0aW9uL2NhcmQvYWZ0ZXItZmFpbGVkLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbC1jcnlwdG8tZXhjaGFu=
Z2UtZnR4LXdpbGwtdHJ5LXRvLXJhaXNlLWZ1bmRzLXNhbS1iYW5rbWFuLWZyaWVkLXRlbGxzLWV=
tcGxveWVlcy1MYkVYVkpNN0x5bExTQ2tSbU8wdw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB70e76afa" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> email to employees</a>, Bankman-Fried also said that =E2=80=9Cprob=
ably [Binance] never really planned to go through with the deal, but so be =
it.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a <em>prank</em>, precipitating a liquidity=
 crisis at a rival, offering to bail it out, and then passing on the bailou=
t by saying that you found a deep hole in due diligence would be very effec=
tive: Binance=E2=80=99s public withdrawal from the deal will likely make it=
 harder for any other potential rescuer to get comfortable with FTX=E2=80=
=99s solvency. If Binance=E2=80=99s goal here was just to destroy FTX, it h=
as played it perfectly. But why would that be the goal?</p>
